  "text": "Following a similar rationale and employing a panel of fourteen developed democracies from 1981 to 1995, [CITATION_1] investigate what drives the remarkable change in contemporary tax policy. They conclude that internationalization, domestic economic change, and budgetary pressures each prompt significant changes in tax policy yet, together, they create a system of constraints altering the level and distribution of tax burden. Regarding the impact of market integration on capital taxation, they find that both capital mobility and trade are associated with cuts in statutory corporate tax rates but not with reductions in effective average tax rates on capital income.",
